      • betweenMinAndMax

        public boolean betweenMinAndMax(SearchKey key)
        Check if the given SearchKey is in the [min, max] of this range. Note that a SearchKey may be in the [min, max] but not match the range.

        For example, assume there is a SearchRange is {1, ALL, 5}. The min of the range is {1, -INT_MAX, 5} and the max of the range is {1, INT_MAX, 5}. A key {1, 2, 3} is the [min, max] but not match {1, ALL, 5}, due to the way of comparing SearchKeys.
        Parameters:
        key - the search key
        Returns:
        whether the key is in the range

      • isSingleValue

        public boolean isSingleValue()
        Check if this range represents a single key. It is also used to check if this range can be converted into a SearchKey.
        Returns:
        if this range represents a single key

      • asSearchKey

        public SearchKey asSearchKey()
        Converts this range into a SearchKey. We expect the caller will call isSingleValue() before calling this method.
        Returns:
        a SearchKey represents the range
